					<div class="commentheading">On July 24, 2009 at 04:07 AM, Dilbert said...</div>
					<div class="commentsubject"></div>
					<div class="commentbody">sandra -<br />
<br />
steel head trout - as best I've been able to research - is genetically the same fish as a fresh water trout - but has adapted to a fresh water / sea water life cycle.  the other major difference noted is steel head do not die after spawning as salmon.  they do return to their headwaters to spawn, but after spawning, return to the sea.<br />
<br />
salmon and trout are genetically "kissing cousins" - but you are spot on - the coloration of steel head is very close to the the color of salmon.  but one must keep in mind "wild" salmon vs. "farmed" salmon.  farmed salmon is usually fed a diet with color agents.  those agents are most often "natural" substances - it's essentially like eating a lot of carrots will turn you orange (extreme, but true....)<br />
<br />
I've never seen "farmed" steel head on offer - don't know if such a thing as "farmed" steel head even exists.  steel head is really a fish eating treat.<br />
<br />
I suspect, but have no first hand experience, you could easily interchange the two - salmon &amp; steel head trout - and only the well seasoned palate could distinguish.</div>
					<hr size="1" noshade />
				
