					<div class="commentheading">On July 31, 2011 at 09:29 PM, Bobby Molden (guest) said...</div>
					<div class="commentsubject">Subject: <span>Gravlax / Dill</span><br /></div>
					<div class="commentbody">My first and only experience in making Gravelax resulted in giving it away to someone that raged ravenous about how good it tasted. To my wife and i, we just could not get past the taste of the dill. It just took over and was overpowering. Perhaps our tastes are a little too fine tuned to the taste of lox which it does resemble. Well, i won't give up yet and purchased a side of salmon about two weeks ago and have been freezing it ever since. I will soon try again and needless to say, the Dill is out. I have read about some of the substitues like fennel, corriander and such but think i will try it minus the above. Less salt, more sugar and contemplating a thin verneer of liquid hickory smoke rubbed on prior to adding the rest of the recipie. Thanks for the site. The info and experiences shared by everyone has been invaluable. Oh" after trying it this way i shall return and give the results. Also, i used a brick last time but may try the water balloon this this time as i do believe that pressure on the flesh of the fish resulted in a firmer cut, making it easier to slice thinly the last time around. Well, thats my two cents and i'm out!</div>
